Well i saw this a while ago. Much like the one in squig but better since its much shorter. Works well you can change the random if you like.  Note it is only returning the string right now. Just use typesend in conjunction with it if you like. Even symbols seem to work so have fun :)

[code]Function HumanText(Text:string):string;
var
  Keyboard:array [1..8] of string;//Declares All vars
  Tempi,i,l,NewKey:integer;
  Temps,Newtext:string;
begin
  keyboard[1]:='1234567890';//Loads your keyboard into all the arrays.
  keyboard[2]:='qwertyuiop';
  keyboard[3]:='asdfghjkl;';
  keyboard[4]:='zxcvbnm,./';
  keyboard[5]:='!@#$%^&*()';
  keyboard[6]:='QWERTYUIOP';
  keyboard[7]:='ASDFGHJKL:';
  keyboard[8]:='ZXCVBNM<>?';
  for l:=1 to length(Text) do//This is like a repeat. But everyloop it automatically adds to I
  begin
    Temps:=copy(Text,l,1)//Just copys a letter in the string into a temporary string var
    if(random(10)=0)then //The randomise of the mistake. So higher it will make LESS mistakes.
    begin
      for i:=1 to 8 do
      begin
        Tempi:=pos(Temps,keyboard[i]) //Loads the POSITION of the letter in the ARRAY
        if(tempi<>0)then
        begin
          if(Tempi=1)then NewKey:=2//If the position in the array is 1 for example Q it cant move to left so it makes sure it goes to right
          if(Tempi=10)then Newkey:=9//Makes sure if pos is 10 it moves to left
          if(Tempi<>1) and (Tempi<>10)then Newkey:=Tempi+random(2)-Random(2)//The random moving bit
          NewText:=copy(keyboard[i],NewKey,1)//Now it puts the NEW letter into the string
          break;
        end;
      end;
    end else Newtext:=Temps//IF the random thing didnt equal 0 then it just keeps the letter the same
  result:=result+Newtext;//Just keeps adding letter bit by bit to the result.
  end;
end;[/code]
